# Picasso Graph Coloring on Cerebras WSE-3 — Session Context

Living document summarizing the architectural state, constraints, open questions,
and design decisions for the Picasso speculative graph coloring implementation on
Cerebras CS-3. Intended to be kept up-to-date across Claude sessions.

---

## Project overview

Picasso list-based speculative graph coloring on Cerebras WSE-3. BSP round:
**speculate → send → recv → barrier → detect/resolve → loop**.
Supports 1D (`width × 1`) and 2D grid layouts. Hash-based partitioning.

## Current production path

- **Routing mode:** SW-relay (checkerboard, 1-hop per task, multi-sender capable)
- **Barrier:**
  - 1D: dedicated colors 8/9/10 on queues 4/5
  - 2D: in-band tokens (4 opcodes) on data colors 0–7 — `is_barrier_packet()`
    check fires on every incoming data wavelet
- **HW-filter code:** present in layout.csl and pe_program.csl but hard-blocked
  at Python entry in `picasso/run_csl_tests.py` for WSE-3

## Routing cost profile (current SW-relay)

| Mode | Per-hop cost | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| 1D | ~15–25 cycles | Task scheduler + send_wavelet drain |
| 2D | ~25–50 cycles | + `is_barrier_packet()` + dest_col division-by-subtraction loop |

## Why HW-filter is blocked on WSE-3

- WSE-3 routers allow only **one `rx` direction per color**
- Interior PEs need both `rx=RAMP` (inject) and `rx=WEST` (forward) — impossible
- Every SDK multi-sender example falls back to 1-hop SW-relay checkerboard
- `color_swap_x` (which would unblock inject+flow dual-color design) is
  "in development" for WSE-3 per Cerebras SDK 2.6 docs
- CE broadcast / CE injection is WSE-2 only per prior repo analysis

